but most importantly, are part of the creative process.

43
00:03:32,748 --> 00:03:34,930
Level designers have authorship of their maps.

44
00:03:36,338 --> 00:03:41,783
From my perspective, a great level brings the most out of the game's narrative and systems.

45
00:03:42,024 --> 00:03:46,408
It captures the imaginations and desire to engage with the content.

46
00:03:46,948 --> 00:03:52,113
It feels like a place or a moment that matters either to the game itself or to the player.

47
00:03:52,133 --> 00:03:57,518
And in those truly great cases, it's something that stays with them after they finish the

48
00:03:57,538 --> 00:03:57,798
game.

49
00:03:57,878 --> 00:03:59,420
They remember and talk about it.

50
00:04:01,306 --> 00:04:04,669
Arcane, as a whole, has a bit of a reputation

51
00:04:05,130 --> 00:04:08,172
for our level design, which a few people think

52
00:04:08,312 --> 00:04:09,013
is pretty good.

53
00:04:10,054 --> 00:04:11,976
I happen to be a big fan, too.

54
00:04:12,937 --> 00:04:15,679
I'm extremely proud to be a part of this team

55
00:04:15,839 --> 00:04:18,041
and admire their work to bits.

56
00:04:25,548 --> 00:04:26,169
So what's the plan?

57
00:04:31,982 --> 00:04:34,103
Okay, it's not this.

58
00:04:35,684 --> 00:04:37,405
The talk is divided into two parts,

59
00:04:38,306 --> 00:04:39,506
your team and processes.

60
00:04:40,147 --> 00:04:41,828
In each part, we'll look at four challenges

61
00:04:42,748 --> 00:04:45,170
you're going to face and look at solutions to each one.

62
00:04:46,331 --> 00:04:47,251
Part one is your team.

63
00:04:48,032 --> 00:04:50,754
The first challenge is an evolving level design team.

64
00:04:51,614 --> 00:04:54,476
Undishonored, we begin with four level designers

65
00:04:54,936 --> 00:04:57,718
who had been working with us since Dark Messiah

66
00:04:58,318 --> 00:05:01,320
and also Unravenholm, LMNO and The Crossing.

67
00:05:02,100 --> 00:05:05,563
with eight new level designers, mostly joining from Arcane Austin.

68
00:05:06,023 --> 00:05:06,964
This is where I started.

69
00:05:06,984 --> 00:05:08,986
I was here.

70
00:05:09,006 --> 00:05:14,129
In Dishonored, we brought in six new level designers to Arcane Léon

71
00:05:14,329 --> 00:05:17,412
because Arcane Austin's LD team began to work on Prey.

72
00:05:18,352 --> 00:05:21,034
Death of the Outsider saw three new level designers join,

73
00:05:21,295 --> 00:05:22,876
and Deathloop added five more.

74
00:05:24,125 --> 00:05:28,107
Over this decade, many team members became leads or specialists.

75
00:05:28,267 --> 00:05:31,689
Some changed to other disciplines while others moved to other studios.

76
00:05:32,409 --> 00:05:35,071
We had an influx constantly of new talent.

77
00:05:35,171 --> 00:05:39,133
But how do you keep your work consistent if your team keeps changing?

78
00:05:40,453 --> 00:05:43,775
It comes down to a clearly defined studio culture,

79
00:05:44,315 --> 00:05:46,876
and that's not something that you can just conjure up.

80
00:05:48,250 --> 00:05:52,936
The ideal is to build a level design team with a foundation and certain design values.

81
00:05:53,457 --> 00:05:58,883
Above all, we are a studio that makes a certain type of game, and we recruit along those values.

82
00:05:59,084 --> 00:06:01,767
Level designers come here to work on that type of game.

83
00:06:02,588 --> 00:06:07,734
Good level design can't just be a value for the LD team. It must extend to the entire studio.

84
00:06:08,962 --> 00:06:10,463
And almost everything in our games

85
00:06:10,683 --> 00:06:12,604
is expressed through the level design.

86
00:06:12,664 --> 00:06:14,965
The whole studio considers level design

87
00:06:15,345 --> 00:06:17,045
as one of the most powerful tools

88
00:06:17,106 --> 00:06:19,486
to deliver the experience that we are all after.

89
00:06:19,506 --> 00:06:23,828
At Arkane, we never shut up about our design values.

90
00:06:23,888 --> 00:06:25,649
We talk about them constantly.

91
00:06:26,149 --> 00:06:27,470
We have posters about them.

92
00:06:30,031 --> 00:06:32,212
I'm sure people are sick of having one brought up

93
00:06:32,312 --> 00:06:35,573
as an argument in meetings, but everyone knows them

94
00:06:35,693 --> 00:06:36,693
and no one forgets them.

95
00:06:37,650 --> 00:06:42,815
I could talk for an hour about Arkane's design values, and many people have, but that's not

96
00:06:42,855 --> 00:06:44,837
the point of this presentation.

97
00:06:45,358 --> 00:06:49,702
The point is that your studio has its own values, and you are the ones defining them.

98
00:06:53,022 --> 00:06:58,526
Our second challenge is leadership bottlenecks. What do I mean by bottleneck? In this case,

99
00:06:58,606 --> 00:07:03,771
it's when an idea doesn't move forward until it works its way up the bottle. A level designer

100
00:07:03,831 --> 00:07:08,655
creates an idea which is reviewed by their lead, who will give feedback, help them iterate,

101
00:07:08,715 --> 00:07:10,576
and ultimately validate it or not.

102
00:07:11,774 --> 00:07:15,136
If validated, the producer will evaluate the impact

103
00:07:15,216 --> 00:07:16,056
on other teams.

104
00:07:16,736 --> 00:07:19,077
Even validated at this stage, which, again,

105
00:07:19,258 --> 00:07:21,839
isn't a given when the creative director gets involved,

106
00:07:22,359 --> 00:07:25,460
who may be reviewing it without the LD present,

107
00:07:26,001 --> 00:07:28,722
they may not feel it fits with the vision of the game

108
00:07:28,862 --> 00:07:29,522
and kill it.

109
00:07:30,743 --> 00:07:33,324
Not only does this weed out a diversity of ideas,

110
00:07:33,424 --> 00:07:34,765
but it could also take weeks.

111
00:07:35,725 --> 00:07:37,186
So what's our solution?

112
00:07:38,606 --> 00:07:40,167
Eliminate the validation process.

113
00:07:44,245 --> 00:07:49,309
No, it's probably not a good idea. Instead, we have a team of leadership.

114
00:07:50,510 --> 00:07:55,415
Our level design team does not have a flat hierarchy, but we have several leaders who

115
00:07:55,455 --> 00:08:00,860
work together. In addition to the lead, there's the campaign designer. Hi, that's me.

116
00:08:01,941 --> 00:08:03,482
And the lead technical level designer.

117
00:08:06,685 --> 00:08:10,869
Together, we sit down with the level designer and review their ideas.

118
00:08:11,832 --> 00:08:16,094
with the campaign producer and the creative director. If one of us can't be present,

119
00:08:16,214 --> 00:08:22,756
the process happens anyway. We keep things moving. We involve the LD so they can defend their ideas,

120
00:08:22,816 --> 00:08:28,818
which then don't have to be validated over and over. Sometimes we disagree, and that's the point.

121
00:08:28,898 --> 00:08:35,000
We have different tastes and areas of expertise. We talk it out. We try to find a consensus or

122
00:08:35,020 --> 00:08:40,942
a compromise. And sometimes we just trust the person who's the most qualified to make that call.

123
00:08:42,215 --> 00:08:45,117
This means a bigger variety of ideas can make it into the game.

124
00:08:46,297 --> 00:08:48,819
OK, so what's each of our areas of expertise?

125
00:08:49,199 --> 00:08:50,680
Who is the most qualified for what?

126
00:08:51,801 --> 00:08:54,623
The lead level designer defines the level design objectives

127
00:08:55,143 --> 00:08:55,764
and guidelines.

128
00:08:56,004 --> 00:08:59,006
They work closely with system design and level art.

129
00:08:59,566 --> 00:09:01,988
The campaign designer crafts the backbone

130
00:09:02,128 --> 00:09:03,188
of the player's experience.

131
00:09:03,609 --> 00:09:07,951
They work closely with narrative and UI and user experience.

132
00:09:08,607 --> 00:09:12,529
The lead technical level designer is all about the team's tools and processes.

133
00:09:12,949 --> 00:09:16,050
They work closely with tools development and tech art.

134
00:09:16,510 --> 00:09:20,492
As you can see, we have a pretty balanced load in terms of what other

135
00:09:20,512 --> 00:09:25,414
disciplines we work with, leading each of us focus on our particular area and

136
00:09:25,794 --> 00:09:28,255
trusting each other to have our backs for the rest.

137
00:09:35,029 --> 00:09:38,390
In a nutshell, discuss ideas together as a group,

138
00:09:38,510 --> 00:09:41,431
not as rungs in a ladder where each rung could break.

139
00:09:42,411 --> 00:09:44,671
We have a variety of leaders with different areas

140
00:09:44,691 --> 00:09:46,592
of expertise and different tastes.

141
00:09:47,412 --> 00:09:50,613
Include the level designer in the validation process.

142
00:09:50,653 --> 00:09:52,213
Let them defend their ideas.

143
00:09:52,813 --> 00:09:55,234
Some people can present their ideas better on paper

144
00:09:55,634 --> 00:09:57,414
and some can do it better in a discussion.

145
00:09:57,734 --> 00:10:00,675
Give them a chance and keep the process moving.

146
00:10:01,435 --> 00:10:03,996
Deference and trust are required.

147
00:10:05,175 --> 00:10:08,178
Challenge three is masters of none.

148
00:10:08,839 --> 00:10:10,140
There is a huge variety of thing

149
00:10:10,280 --> 00:10:11,882
a level designer has to be good at.

150
00:10:14,545 --> 00:10:15,846
You know, jack of all trades.

151
00:10:17,087 --> 00:10:18,989
A level designer creates the maps layout,

152
00:10:19,409 --> 00:10:22,392
the challenges, the logic of events, and so much more.

153
00:10:23,213 --> 00:10:24,654
Every choice a level designer makes

154
00:10:24,715 --> 00:10:26,777
can impact or define the narrative.

155
00:10:27,268 --> 00:10:30,549
Every vignette involves a UI or user experience element,

156
00:10:30,589 --> 00:10:32,109
whether it's an interaction prompt

157
00:10:32,489 --> 00:10:33,930
or an objective notification.

158
00:10:34,630 --> 00:10:37,051
Many game systems happen inside the level design.

159
00:10:37,371 --> 00:10:39,991
How does the map's design get the most out of those systems?

160
00:10:40,532 --> 00:10:43,492
Does the gray box layout match the architectural intentions

161
00:10:43,552 --> 00:10:46,373
with the right proportions, scales, and rhythms of spaces?

162
00:10:46,733 --> 00:10:48,794
Is the map following all metrics and constraints

163
00:10:49,074 --> 00:10:50,374
and optimization guidelines?

164
00:10:50,675 --> 00:10:52,875
Is the level designer an expert on every tool,

165
00:10:53,095 --> 00:10:55,556
including scripting logic and various forms of markup?

166
00:10:57,713 --> 00:11:03,958
This is a lot and no one person can be an expert at all of it. I know I am not.

167
00:11:04,859 --> 00:11:07,301
So what can we do to mitigate it?

168
00:11:08,703 --> 00:11:15,088
The diversification of level design specializations. This is dividing level designers into two types

169
00:11:15,929 --> 00:11:17,930
map owners and specialists.

170
00:11:21,213 --> 00:11:25,897
Specialists ease the burdens on map owners. A narrative scripter.

171
00:11:26,567 --> 00:11:30,530
is part of the narrative team, but with a level designer's skills, this allows them

172
00:11:30,590 --> 00:11:34,052
to autonomously carry out narrative setup in the maps.

173
00:11:34,917 --> 00:11:42,640
The campaign designer makes sure the UI is in sync with what the level designers are doing and guides the LDs on how to best take advantage of it.

174
00:11:43,200 --> 00:11:47,662
A level systems designer can be one or the other, but has the skills in both.

175
00:11:48,082 --> 00:11:56,766
They provide an LD's insight into the development of some systems and assist LDs in getting the most out of those systems.

176
00:11:58,201 --> 00:12:01,162
Level artists work directly with level designers

177
00:12:01,362 --> 00:12:02,202
on the geometry.

178
00:12:02,722 --> 00:12:05,642
So LDs don't also have to be masters

179
00:12:05,723 --> 00:12:07,523
of the fundamentals of architecture,

180
00:12:07,543 --> 00:12:10,784
needing to create gray boxes that transition beautifully

181
00:12:10,824 --> 00:12:12,164
into realistic buildings.

182
00:12:12,704 --> 00:12:14,844
That's not the point of our gray boxes.

183
00:12:15,645 --> 00:12:18,065
Tech LDs assist in tools development,

184
00:12:18,105 --> 00:12:20,266
but also work with level designers

185
00:12:20,386 --> 00:12:21,926
on highly technical tasks.

186
00:12:23,146 --> 00:12:25,107
This has helped Arkane so much.

187
00:12:26,385 --> 00:12:29,767
It is not necessary for map owners to be experts at everything.

188
00:12:30,187 --> 00:12:33,348
There are people on other teams who have level design skills.

189
00:12:33,448 --> 00:12:34,649
Let them contribute.

190
00:12:35,409 --> 00:12:39,370
But most importantly, be sensitive to what each member of your team needs.

191
00:12:40,291 --> 00:12:42,092
They don't all have to be map owners.

192
00:12:42,212 --> 00:12:45,833
Let one focus on technical tasks and another work on narrative.

193
00:12:46,533 --> 00:12:48,074
Let them focus on their strengths.

194
00:12:49,386 --> 00:12:52,267
Challenge four is overwhelming dependencies.

195
00:12:52,947 --> 00:12:54,728
No discipline works in isolation,

196
00:12:54,928 --> 00:12:57,049
and game development has many moving parts.

197
00:12:57,549 --> 00:13:00,250
The whole design must work with nearly all of them.

198
00:13:01,891 --> 00:13:02,931
But what does that look like?

199
00:13:04,012 --> 00:13:06,053
What are a level designer's key partnerships?

200
00:13:11,015 --> 00:13:13,456
First, what is the work that happens

201
00:13:13,516 --> 00:13:15,276
before level designers begin?

202
00:13:15,537 --> 00:13:17,037
What allows them to do their work?

203
00:13:18,307 --> 00:13:22,307
In defining the shape and scope, many questions have to be asked.

204
00:13:22,727 --> 00:13:25,988
The broadest one is, what does a level even mean in our game?

205
00:13:26,348 --> 00:13:28,028
Are the levels connected by ellipses,

206
00:13:28,108 --> 00:13:29,129
or are they contiguous?

207
00:13:29,609 --> 00:13:30,549
How big are the maps?

208
00:13:30,989 --> 00:13:31,869
How dense are they?

209
00:13:32,169 --> 00:13:34,710
Do several maps make a level, like we had in Dishonored?

210
00:13:34,970 --> 00:13:36,450
Or is it something else entirely,

211
00:13:36,510 --> 00:13:38,270
like we're currently doing in Deathloop?

212
00:13:39,251 --> 00:13:43,772
It's critical that the technical director and level designers

213
00:13:44,072 --> 00:13:46,952
are in sync with creative direction and art direction.

214
00:13:47,749 --> 00:13:50,010
If they're not, be careful.

215
00:13:50,530 --> 00:13:53,812
What feels like the final decision can change,

216
00:13:54,352 --> 00:13:56,293
and it will be painful if it does.

217
00:13:57,554 --> 00:13:59,615
Engine and tools developers have a hand

218
00:13:59,695 --> 00:14:03,036
in laying the foundation for the ways LDs and level artists do

219
00:14:03,076 --> 00:14:06,038
their work, or what work is even possible at all.

220
00:14:07,438 --> 00:14:09,940
To ensure that these tools fit the needs and processes

221
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:13,962
of both teams, tech LDs and tech artists are involved early.

222
00:14:14,622 --> 00:14:15,382
Tools are created.

223
00:14:15,837 --> 00:14:17,118
Workflows are mapped out.

224
00:14:17,578 --> 00:14:18,959
Best practices are defined.

225
00:14:19,519 --> 00:14:21,901
Now LDs and level artists have exactly what they need,

226
00:14:22,322 --> 00:14:23,843
tools that are concretely designed

227
00:14:24,383 --> 00:14:26,065
for the exact work they're doing.

228
00:14:26,785 --> 00:14:29,667
Now and then we try to do something wacky,

229
00:14:30,248 --> 00:14:32,790
like this honor to time travel mission,

230
00:14:32,890 --> 00:14:35,372
crack in the slab or the clockwork mansion.

231
00:14:36,593 --> 00:14:39,215
Our engine and tools teams have the flexibility

232
00:14:39,275 --> 00:14:40,696
to make our dreams come true.

233
00:14:42,297 --> 00:14:44,417
But we don't just use tools to build maps.

234
00:14:44,497 --> 00:14:46,738
We also need to implement game systems.

235
00:14:47,538 --> 00:14:50,499
Technical LDs will work alongside the systems designers

236
00:14:50,699 --> 00:14:53,800
in a mix of engine developers and gameplay programmers.

237
00:14:54,540 --> 00:14:58,461
The work done by these teams is critical

238
00:14:58,501 --> 00:14:59,801
to making immersive Sims.

239
00:15:00,901 --> 00:15:03,162
Void Studio is built from the ground up

240
00:15:03,222 --> 00:15:04,762
for exactly this type of game.

241
00:15:05,363 --> 00:15:08,063
We've created a visual scripting language called Kiskul,

242
00:15:08,283 --> 00:15:09,724
tailored exactly to our needs

243
00:15:09,864 --> 00:15:11,284
and the needs of the games we're making.

244
00:15:11,902 --> 00:15:19,566
We have a modular component system that ensures behaviors are consistent game-wide, which is a key to systemic game design.

245
00:15:20,227 --> 00:15:24,490
We have external tools like a content integration system or performance monitors,

246
00:15:24,990 --> 00:15:32,455
but we sometimes like to give them funny names like Octung that delivers warnings or Tintin, our bug reporter.

247
00:15:40,338 --> 00:15:44,722
but narrative and gameplay are one. What the story is and what the player can or

248
00:15:44,902 --> 00:15:50,086
must do are intertwined. This forms the campaign. The campaign designer will

249
00:15:50,106 --> 00:15:54,430
collaborate closely with narrative team, lead level design, and creative direction

250
00:15:54,550 --> 00:15:57,333
to form the high-level outline of the player's goals.

251
00:15:58,076 --> 00:16:02,859
They then collaborate with the LDs to turn this outline into detailed scenarios, challenges, and vignettes.

252
00:16:03,740 --> 00:16:08,102
The game world is fleshed out from a collaboration between level design, narrative, and art direction.

253
00:16:08,783 --> 00:16:12,465
A level design problem can lead to a solution that makes the game's world richer.

254
00:16:13,225 --> 00:16:17,848
Once narrative and art get a hold of it, what was a problem now fleshes out the world.

255
00:16:18,490 --> 00:16:21,633
In Dishonored, we wanted urban maps, which implies streets,

256
00:16:21,993 --> 00:16:24,415
but we also didn't want to put up invisible walls.

257
00:16:24,895 --> 00:16:27,837
So art and narrative invented massive street blockers,

258
00:16:27,877 --> 00:16:30,860
which fictionally controlled the spread of the plague,

259
00:16:31,300 --> 00:16:33,261
but also enclosed the gameplay space.

260
00:16:34,422 --> 00:16:38,405
A narrative designer may propose something surprising.

261
00:16:38,909 --> 00:16:41,250
A concept artist runs with it, exciting everyone,

262
00:16:41,330 --> 00:16:43,612
leading to a level designer creating a vignette,

263
00:16:43,992 --> 00:16:45,773
or maybe an entire level around it.

264
00:16:46,213 --> 00:16:49,435
But this can only happen if each team member is attentive

265
00:16:49,475 --> 00:16:51,736
to one another and feels free to collaborate.

266
00:16:51,756 --> 00:16:54,517
Now we're in the thick of it.

267
00:16:56,038 --> 00:16:59,200
What keep partnership come into play while the level geometry

268
00:16:59,360 --> 00:16:59,960
is being made?

269
00:17:02,982 --> 00:17:06,563
The crafters of the maps may be our most important partnership.

270
00:17:07,368 --> 00:17:10,690
The level designer and level artist will begin work at the same time.

271
00:17:11,531 --> 00:17:15,654
The LD creates the layout and flow of the maps in Graybox,

272
00:17:16,274 --> 00:17:20,097
which establishes the size, scope, paths, basically what the level is.

273
00:17:21,237 --> 00:17:24,340
The level artist creates the visual DNA of the map.

274
00:17:24,760 --> 00:17:29,543
This proof of concept establishes the scale and proportions, the style and the mood.

275
00:17:33,875 --> 00:17:40,178
forces. The level artists are not doing an art pass on the maps. They're creating a new map

276
00:17:40,559 --> 00:17:45,461
from scratch based on the LD's layout but with the visual DNA of their proof of concept.

277
00:17:46,061 --> 00:17:50,704
Pairs of level designers and level artists will work together until the end of the project,

278
00:17:51,184 --> 00:17:53,965
collaborating to bring their combined vision to reality.

279
00:17:55,127 --> 00:17:57,628
Level artists work closely with environment artists

280
00:17:57,668 --> 00:18:00,409
to establish a modular system called a breakout kit

281
00:18:00,569 --> 00:18:01,850
that can be snapped together.

282
00:18:01,870 --> 00:18:04,791
These are intended to be replaced with authored assets

283
00:18:04,871 --> 00:18:06,692
late in production during the polish stage.

284
00:18:07,292 --> 00:18:09,613
Level designers also work with environment artists

285
00:18:09,673 --> 00:18:11,114
to create unique props.

286
00:18:11,854 --> 00:18:15,115
This can be a complicated process involving concept art

287
00:18:15,495 --> 00:18:16,436
and level art as well,

288
00:18:16,796 --> 00:18:18,456
and can require a lot of iteration

289
00:18:18,536 --> 00:18:20,837
since this piece may be part of a puzzle

290
00:18:20,877 --> 00:18:23,438
that players need to understand just by looking at it.

291
00:18:24,358 --> 00:18:28,523
The moving bank vault in Death of the Outsider was constructed by someone who could do both

292
00:18:28,623 --> 00:18:30,425
concept art and environment art.

293
00:18:32,151 --> 00:18:36,072
Concept artists will absolutely become involved to visualize the spaces,

294
00:18:36,452 --> 00:18:40,733
doing paint-overs of the gray box or the level artist's rough blockout.

295
00:18:41,413 --> 00:18:44,434
Sometimes this can bring out new ideas, with the concept artist

296
00:18:44,834 --> 00:18:47,254
providing a vision neither map owner had anticipated.

297
00:18:47,835 --> 00:18:52,216
Practically speaking, it is useful to define the details that the environment

298
00:18:52,276 --> 00:18:55,576
and lighting artists will use. Other times it's just exciting.

299
00:18:56,056 --> 00:18:59,377
You get to see what the map could look like in the finished game, possibly years

300
00:18:59,437 --> 00:19:01,798
before the art and rendering are ready to make it possible.

301
00:19:02,438 --> 00:19:06,721
It can be an inspiring moment that invigorates the passions of everyone involved.

302
00:19:07,821 --> 00:19:09,582
But we require illumination.

303
00:19:10,123 --> 00:19:12,844
Our level design and level art wouldn't mean much without lighting.

304
00:19:14,385 --> 00:19:15,606
How would the players see?

305
00:19:19,048 --> 00:19:24,211
Once a map's layout is stable, a lighting artist steps in and the three will work together.

306
00:19:24,231 --> 00:19:29,435
A map's lighting could be subtle and functional, there but never thought about.

307
00:19:29,936 --> 00:19:34,139
or it can be emotional, heavily pushing the desired mood, or it can be directional,

308
00:19:34,399 --> 00:19:37,381
giving the player critical information, guiding them forward.

309
00:19:38,102 --> 00:19:41,404
Delighting artists will use all of these methods to make the map shine.

310
00:19:41,424 --> 00:19:43,025
Pun intended.

311
00:19:43,045 --> 00:19:49,630
Environmental storytelling is the multitude of stories that exist in all spaces in the game.

312
00:19:50,754 --> 00:19:57,518
expressed either explicitly or left to inference. It has two forms. High level is, why does this

313
00:19:57,538 --> 00:20:04,663
space exist? Why is this place like this? It is often conceived by the narrative team, creative

314
00:20:04,703 --> 00:20:11,487
direction, and level art leadership. This forms the core concept of a location. Low level is,

315
00:20:11,507 --> 00:20:15,570
what happened here? What do these objects communicate to the player?

316
00:20:16,692 --> 00:20:18,293
Low level comes from all directions,

317
00:20:18,813 --> 00:20:20,434
often proposed by the narrative team,

318
00:20:20,474 --> 00:20:22,476
but just as often from the level designers

319
00:20:22,656 --> 00:20:23,617
or the level artists.

320
00:20:25,458 --> 00:20:28,400
Constructing the level geometry is now well in progress,

321
00:20:28,520 --> 00:20:29,941
but we're making games.

322
00:20:30,161 --> 00:20:31,222
What about the gameplay?

323
00:20:32,363 --> 00:20:33,504
What about taking a drink?

324
00:20:33,564 --> 00:20:35,185
Because my throat is getting worn out.

325
00:20:40,509 --> 00:20:41,910
Just as we have emergent gameplay,

326
00:20:42,771 --> 00:20:44,051
we have emergent level design.

327
00:20:44,602 --> 00:20:48,064
R-level designers have a lot of freedom to invent wild bullshit.

328
00:20:48,905 --> 00:20:52,327
The work done by the systems designer and gameplay programmers

329
00:20:52,807 --> 00:20:57,471
allows LDs to invent novel, weird, or just plain game-breaking stuff that

330
00:20:58,471 --> 00:21:01,514
they create new uses for everything.

331
00:21:02,354 --> 00:21:02,995
It's not uncommon.

332
00:21:03,848 --> 00:21:05,929
for an LD to push the envelope with our tools

333
00:21:05,989 --> 00:21:08,451
and create a spaghetti pile of logic

334
00:21:08,511 --> 00:21:09,611
just to get it working.

335
00:21:10,232 --> 00:21:12,473
Yes, I am very guilty of this.

336
00:21:13,213 --> 00:21:16,115
I think it's great, but we still must be careful.

337
00:21:17,236 --> 00:21:20,017
This is when tech LDs and gameplay programmers

338
00:21:20,077 --> 00:21:21,558
and systems designers get involved.

339
00:21:22,328 --> 00:21:25,010
It could be coded into a fully supported new feature.

340
00:21:25,450 --> 00:21:27,531
This is a best case scenario for everyone,

341
00:21:27,631 --> 00:21:29,012
and it happens very often.

342
00:21:29,793 --> 00:21:32,414
It could be cleaned up and optimized by the tech LDs.

343
00:21:32,655 --> 00:21:34,536
Even without code support, a specialist

344
00:21:34,576 --> 00:21:37,998
can do a lot with our tools in either outcome.

345
00:21:38,638 --> 00:21:40,540
It can become a nightmare for QA.

346
00:21:41,020 --> 00:21:43,362
This is especially true if they come across what

347
00:21:43,382 --> 00:21:45,083
looks like a new feature, but there's

348
00:21:45,183 --> 00:21:47,264
no documentation and no metrics.

349
00:21:47,584 --> 00:21:49,806
And the only person who even knows it exists

350
00:21:50,206 --> 00:21:52,007
is the level designer who cobbled it together.

351
00:21:54,932 --> 00:21:58,072
Player affordance is near and dear to our hearts at Arkane,

352
00:21:58,413 --> 00:22:02,174
expressed simply, if it looks doable, let the player do it.

353
00:22:02,554 --> 00:22:05,254
But also, if we can't let the player do it,

354
00:22:05,834 --> 00:22:07,435
don't let it look doable.

355
00:22:08,515 --> 00:22:10,936
This is expressed through a union of environment art,

356
00:22:11,456 --> 00:22:13,757
level art, and systems design.

357
00:22:14,917 --> 00:22:16,797
Level designers will define rules

358
00:22:16,877 --> 00:22:19,898
about what looks interactive or what looks traversable.

359
00:22:20,298 --> 00:22:21,399
Can I fit into that tunnel?

360
00:22:21,959 --> 00:22:22,899
Can I open this door?

361
00:22:23,770 --> 00:22:24,811
It looks like I can.

362
00:22:26,111 --> 00:22:28,312
Systems design will set the player's expectations

363
00:22:28,352 --> 00:22:29,372
for combat tactics.

364
00:22:29,832 --> 00:22:33,213
Like how big of a gap can an enemy see through,

365
00:22:33,413 --> 00:22:35,154
or what counts as cover and what doesn't?

366
00:22:35,174 --> 00:22:38,075
Environment artists interpret these guidelines,

367
00:22:38,115 --> 00:22:40,075
but they're often the start of the conversation.

368
00:22:40,555 --> 00:22:42,316
They may want to make a certain type of asset,

369
00:22:42,356 --> 00:22:43,836
like a box of fireworks.

370
00:22:44,877 --> 00:22:48,138
Well, if the player shoots it, he'll expect it to explode.

371
00:22:51,530 --> 00:22:53,612
We achieve a narrative rooted in gameplay

372
00:22:53,652 --> 00:22:56,354
through level design, systems design, and narrative design,

373
00:22:56,414 --> 00:22:59,236
bouncing ideas off each other, letting them evolve.

374
00:22:59,896 --> 00:23:00,677
Here's one example.

375
00:23:01,337 --> 00:23:03,038
Narrative decides that the protagonist

376
00:23:03,058 --> 00:23:04,519
should have a personalized weapon

377
00:23:04,760 --> 00:23:06,000
that expresses their themes.

378
00:23:06,621 --> 00:23:08,242
And Death of the Outsider, Billie Lurk,

379
00:23:08,342 --> 00:23:10,724
had a voltaic gun that represented

380
00:23:10,784 --> 00:23:13,626
her unconventional methods and pragmatic ingenuity.

381
00:23:14,566 --> 00:23:18,829
Systems design devises a unique ammo type,

382
00:23:19,150 --> 00:23:20,371
pencils and pens.

383
00:23:21,642 --> 00:23:26,083
Level design could then have you visiting locations where pens and pencils are laying around.

384
00:23:26,624 --> 00:23:27,904
Say, why not a bank?

385
00:23:29,825 --> 00:23:31,225
It can move in the other direction.

386
00:23:31,685 --> 00:23:32,926
Level design creates a puzzle.

387
00:23:34,066 --> 00:23:35,747
There's a button that you have to shoot.

388
00:23:36,267 --> 00:23:41,209
Systems design invents a rubber bullet that can impact silently and then be recovered.

389
00:23:41,829 --> 00:23:46,511
Narrative design, oops, narrative design brings a tool into the games world.

390
00:23:47,432 --> 00:23:48,732
I think it was part of a fish.

391
00:23:50,358 --> 00:23:51,579
but players can't read our minds.

392
00:23:52,739 --> 00:23:55,341
The game has to communicate possibilities in play,

393
00:23:55,921 --> 00:23:58,143
what is allowed and what is needed to progress.

394
00:23:58,843 --> 00:24:01,504
The campaign designer will work with level designers

395
00:24:01,604 --> 00:24:03,966
to transmute their designs into communication

396
00:24:04,086 --> 00:24:05,647
via the user interface.

397
00:24:06,527 --> 00:24:09,209
This can take a lot of forms like objective texts

398
00:24:09,349 --> 00:24:12,871
or markers on the HUD, a quest journal or failure states.

399
00:24:13,891 --> 00:24:15,953
The narrative team is involved from the start,

400
00:24:16,293 --> 00:24:17,774
weaving story through objectives

401
00:24:17,854 --> 00:24:19,194
and doing the final writing pass.

402
00:24:20,767 --> 00:24:27,491
So now the map exists. What happens next? A static map is not an immersive map. What brings the maps to life?

403
00:24:30,993 --> 00:24:37,918
Sound designers, VFX artists, and animators work directly in our maps to create vibrant,

404
00:24:38,418 --> 00:24:41,960
reactive, living places using the same tools as the LDs.

405
00:24:42,801 --> 00:24:45,862
These team members are artists and designers and may see a way.

406
00:24:46,799 --> 00:24:52,043
to do something a bit differently than what the LD asked for, who doesn't have the same eye for this kind of work.

407
00:24:52,924 --> 00:24:57,068
In the Clockwork Mansion, the electro-shock sequence was pitched as being quite subtle.

408
00:24:58,169 --> 00:25:01,171
These three teams punched up the intensity over and over,

409
00:25:02,072 --> 00:25:07,116
both trying to reward the player with a dramatic outcome and drive home the horror of what you were doing.

410
00:25:08,017 --> 00:25:13,661
This couldn't happen if these teams just had a list of assets with no context and no say in how they're used.

411
00:25:14,755 --> 00:25:18,440
There's a deep symbiosis between systems design and animators.

412
00:25:19,001 --> 00:25:21,043
Together they bring the NPCs to life.

413
00:25:21,544 --> 00:25:25,129
But shit gets real when L-level designers are involved.

414
00:25:26,670 --> 00:25:29,573
The level design could be causing trouble for NPCs.

415
00:25:29,653 --> 00:25:32,395
The player could often be crouched inside a low tunnel,

416
00:25:32,455 --> 00:25:34,858
leaving enemies baffled, even though they're within reach.

417
00:25:35,558 --> 00:25:38,080
Animators could step in and create a new set of animations

418
00:25:38,180 --> 00:25:38,861
to solve this.

419
00:25:39,642 --> 00:25:41,804
Level designers could need to convey something

420
00:25:42,104 --> 00:25:42,844
about the area.

421
00:25:42,924 --> 00:25:44,426
Maybe a dust storm has started,

422
00:25:44,806 --> 00:25:46,267
which is hazardous to the player.

423
00:25:46,628 --> 00:25:48,910
The animators have the NPCs bracing themselves

424
00:25:48,970 --> 00:25:50,071
and shielding their eyes,

425
00:25:50,531 --> 00:25:52,373
making it clear without exposition.

426
00:25:53,793 --> 00:25:56,214
Animators can push hard on certain behaviors,

427
00:25:56,674 --> 00:25:58,194
taking it beyond what was proposed.

428
00:25:58,795 --> 00:26:00,815
Our games have a feature we call distractions,

429
00:26:00,875 --> 00:26:04,357
where NPCs move off their patrols to do a trivial action.

430
00:26:05,137 --> 00:26:06,257
A handful of them would do,

431
00:26:06,317 --> 00:26:08,738
but our animators create dozens and dozens.

432
00:26:10,039 --> 00:26:11,759
In a vivid and tactile world,

433
00:26:11,960 --> 00:26:14,220
so much is communicated through sound.

434
00:26:15,381 --> 00:26:16,921
A button is modeled and animated.

435
00:26:17,462 --> 00:26:19,882
The sound is what makes it feel like you pressed it.

436
00:26:20,303 --> 00:26:20,903
There's that click.

437
00:26:21,225 --> 00:26:22,766
and then the machine roars to life,

438
00:26:22,886 --> 00:26:25,448
or maybe it gives a dull, empty sound and a crackle.

439
00:26:25,889 --> 00:26:27,510
Maybe there's something about the sound

440
00:26:27,550 --> 00:26:30,031
that tells you the machine needs power or is broken,

441
00:26:30,492 --> 00:26:33,774
or if it does turn on, it will only stay on for a short time.

442
00:26:34,735 --> 00:26:37,376
Sound can communicate in intuitive ways,

443
00:26:37,476 --> 00:26:41,519
instinctive ways that are faster and more intuitive

444
00:26:41,559 --> 00:26:45,001
than a UI prompt or the player character explaining things.

445
00:26:46,075 --> 00:26:48,497
So much of what you see can also be heard.

446
00:26:49,117 --> 00:26:52,280
Atmosphere is equally visual as auditory.

447
00:26:52,300 --> 00:26:54,782
Tech artists and rendering engineers

448
00:26:54,882 --> 00:26:57,904
create visceral experiences with the sound designers.

449
00:26:58,465 --> 00:27:01,667
The gentle hum in the background perfectly matching

450
00:27:01,727 --> 00:27:05,070
the haze surrounding you, the crunching under your feet

451
00:27:05,130 --> 00:27:07,332
letting you feel the shaders on the ground.

452
00:27:07,932 --> 00:27:09,533
The player will feel like they're there.

453
00:27:10,034 --> 00:27:11,235
The map is now a place.

454
00:27:12,636 --> 00:27:14,177
Details tell a story.

455
00:27:14,829 --> 00:27:19,511
A light touch of VFX can deepen the player's involvement in what the LDs and level artists

456
00:27:19,531 --> 00:27:20,011
have built.

457
00:27:20,612 --> 00:27:24,454
You could add flies over a trash can next to a door to tip the player off that that

458
00:27:24,534 --> 00:27:27,795
house isn't abandoned and something fishy is going on in there.

459
00:27:28,456 --> 00:27:32,538
Beams of light through cracks in the ceiling signal that your long journey back to the

460
00:27:32,578 --> 00:27:33,759
surface has come to an end.

461
00:27:34,599 --> 00:27:38,341
Maybe this is an exciting moment of relief or a weary, somber moment.

462
00:27:38,461 --> 00:27:41,943
The way the beams of light move can push either feeling.

463
00:27:43,059 --> 00:27:47,163
A cloud of dust could appear when moving an object, deepening the feeling of intruding

464
00:27:47,504 --> 00:27:48,665
upon a forgotten place.

465
00:27:49,366 --> 00:27:52,469
Details like these aren't just immersive, they carry information.

466
00:27:52,890 --> 00:27:55,773
The player can learn or understand without realizing that they have.

467
00:27:56,855 --> 00:27:57,375
And finally...

468
00:27:58,375 --> 00:27:59,455
How does all of this work?

469
00:28:00,595 --> 00:28:03,136
How do you get this work into the player's hands?

470
00:28:03,356 --> 00:28:04,356
How do we get there?

471
00:28:05,336 --> 00:28:06,837
Someone has to keep the ship afloat,

472
00:28:07,017 --> 00:28:08,517
and eventually you need to ship.

473
00:28:09,237 --> 00:28:11,638
Our testing teams are divided between quality assurance

474
00:28:11,818 --> 00:28:12,818
and dev testing.

475
00:28:13,358 --> 00:28:15,939
Typically, QA testers will be assigned maps

476
00:28:16,079 --> 00:28:17,219
or parts of the campaign,

477
00:28:17,659 --> 00:28:20,040
and switch every few months to keep ideas fresh.

478
00:28:20,800 --> 00:28:23,561
A dev tester will attend each weekly level design meeting,

479
00:28:23,641 --> 00:28:26,301
so their dev team always has the latest info

480
00:28:26,321 --> 00:28:27,461
on what the LDs are up to.

481
00:28:28,662 --> 00:28:34,607
big complex features that are tied deeply to level design make a special focus from a dev tester who

482
00:28:34,647 --> 00:28:41,232
attend the kickoff meeting and provide feedback. Players usually like all of the frames per second.

483
00:28:42,549 --> 00:28:47,131
Optimization is both the first and last thing our technical teams work on in a production.

484
00:28:48,012 --> 00:28:53,994
Our game systems are CPU heavy, so from day one everything is designed with optimization in mind.

485
00:28:54,635 --> 00:28:59,537
This impacts the scope and density of our maps. If you run afoul of this, you may need to split

486
00:28:59,557 --> 00:29:05,760
your map in two or three or four. And that's harder than it sounds. It will define how many

487
00:29:05,860 --> 00:29:08,281
active AI can be at a location at once.

488
00:29:08,894 --> 00:29:13,396
We have to do all sorts of tricks to limit this invisibly without making the maps feel empty.

489
00:29:14,096 --> 00:29:18,437
