551
00:33:08,768 --> 00:33:12,330
and a passionate dedication to immersion and world building.

552
00:33:13,111 --> 00:33:14,592
There's a balance that has to be reached

553
00:33:14,652 --> 00:33:17,154
between what feels best for the player

554
00:33:17,775 --> 00:33:21,037
and strict adherence to the metrics that are still needed

555
00:33:21,397 --> 00:33:23,439
to make any of our game systems even work.

556
00:33:24,740 --> 00:33:26,501
We need flexible metrics.

557
00:33:27,976 --> 00:33:32,658
you can't know how any of the metrics will work in gameplay until the level designers are using

558
00:33:32,698 --> 00:33:41,001
them and testing their limits. The metrics for enemy vision range may not work with the sight

559
00:33:41,021 --> 00:33:45,983
lines the level designers need. The level geometry may require many iterations with

560
00:33:46,023 --> 00:33:51,745
gameplay programmers to find the correct metrics for enemy pathfinding. Your tools could be

561
00:33:51,785 --> 00:33:54,886
displaying warnings when the metrics are broken, which is good,

562
00:33:55,774 --> 00:33:58,016
but this can also stifle experimentation.

563
00:33:58,636 --> 00:34:01,719
Designers like to go off the rails when trying a new idea.

564
00:34:01,739 --> 00:34:04,282
The engine will often put strict limits

565
00:34:04,382 --> 00:34:06,604
on how many NPCs can be near the player,

566
00:34:06,704 --> 00:34:08,506
but level and narrative design

567
00:34:08,546 --> 00:34:10,287
have the player crashing a party.

568
00:34:11,348 --> 00:34:14,672
Oh no, the engine says you can only have five NPCs

569
00:34:15,092 --> 00:34:15,713
at the party.

570
00:34:15,733 --> 00:34:19,036
The interaction range on pickups.

571
00:34:19,612 --> 00:34:21,913
may be too large for the object density of the maps,

572
00:34:22,033 --> 00:34:23,533
making it difficult for the player

573
00:34:23,573 --> 00:34:25,434
to target one item over another.

574
00:34:26,374 --> 00:34:28,855
Metrics on audio propagation say that sound can't

575
00:34:28,896 --> 00:34:30,316
travel more than 20 meters.

576
00:34:30,496 --> 00:34:32,797
But level and audio designers are

577
00:34:32,837 --> 00:34:34,798
placing diegetic music in the maps, which

578
00:34:34,898 --> 00:34:36,259
now cuts off awkwardly.

579
00:34:37,439 --> 00:34:40,360
Everything the level artists and environment artists planned

580
00:34:40,500 --> 00:34:42,181
could fly to bits when it crashes

581
00:34:42,241 --> 00:34:43,602
into what the LDs have done.

582
00:34:44,122 --> 00:34:45,503
These metrics are a starting point.

583
00:34:46,063 --> 00:34:47,463
But for the collaboration to work,

584
00:34:47,543 --> 00:34:49,064
both teams need to be flexible.

585
00:34:49,939 --> 00:34:53,841
The complexity of the objectives may be too great for the space on the UI.

586
00:34:54,401 --> 00:34:58,643
Three words to explain the next goal may work in 90% of the cases,

587
00:34:58,743 --> 00:35:00,363
but sometimes you need more room.

588
00:35:01,324 --> 00:35:01,764
To be clear.

589
00:35:02,997 --> 00:35:04,198
be as flexible as possible.

590
00:35:04,478 --> 00:35:06,218
But something simply can't change.

591
00:35:06,918 --> 00:35:08,679
Character limits on UI elements have

592
00:35:08,719 --> 00:35:10,459
to take into account localization.

593
00:35:10,960 --> 00:35:13,160
Some languages will need twice as much space.

594
00:35:13,960 --> 00:35:15,721
If level designers experiment forever,

595
00:35:15,861 --> 00:35:18,542
expecting systems and gameplay programmers to keep up,

596
00:35:18,922 --> 00:35:20,622
they won't be able to stabilize the game

597
00:35:20,642 --> 00:35:21,723
into a shippable state.

598
00:35:22,543 --> 00:35:23,843
As annoying as many of the warnings

599
00:35:23,903 --> 00:35:25,784
a level designer will butt up against are,

600
00:35:25,864 --> 00:35:28,345
they exist for a reason and build management.

601
00:35:28,859 --> 00:35:33,380
will pay the price in hours and sanity for every warning a level designer ignores.

602
00:35:34,421 --> 00:35:40,022
A level designer may want to go wild with massive VFX and sounds that propagate across the entire

603
00:35:40,102 --> 00:35:45,904
map, but eventually they'll hit a limit on what the engine can do if the level designer requests

604
00:35:46,064 --> 00:35:51,686
something as innocent as changing the height of a table. This can cause a domino effect.

605
00:35:52,528 --> 00:35:55,330
with hours of rework for animation and character art.

606
00:35:55,850 --> 00:35:58,572
These changes must be requested with extreme caution.

607
00:35:58,612 --> 00:36:01,954
You probably won't get a second chance if you're wrong.

608
00:36:03,034 --> 00:36:04,915
It's a difficult process, but there's

609
00:36:04,955 --> 00:36:08,077
some things the team can do to make it go more smoothly.

610
00:36:08,938 --> 00:36:10,739
Environment artists can get a hold

611
00:36:10,799 --> 00:36:14,561
of the metrics created by systems design and animation

612
00:36:14,741 --> 00:36:14,961
early.

613
00:36:15,516 --> 00:36:21,066
and make a modular grey box kit that will match the breakout kit they'll later make for the level artists.

614
00:36:21,748 --> 00:36:26,297
