00:56:14,308 --> 00:56:17,611
need tasks to review them and point out errors.

987
00:56:18,511 --> 00:56:21,814
I do a lot of doc work for the campaign.

988
00:56:21,994 --> 00:56:23,475
I have a pretty clear overview,

989
00:56:23,896 --> 00:56:27,239
but it's extremely helpful to have level designers

990
00:56:27,659 --> 00:56:29,340
come in, look at the details,

991
00:56:29,460 --> 00:56:31,302
and know where I've made a mistake.

992
00:56:33,384 --> 00:56:33,584
Yes.

993
00:56:35,136 --> 00:56:38,657
Redundancy is a surefire way to get misleading docs.

994
00:56:38,918 --> 00:56:42,359
You need things like data boxes that exist on multiple pages

995
00:56:42,419 --> 00:56:44,120
and only need to be updated once.

996
00:56:44,960 --> 00:56:47,641
Old stuff is often good to keep,

997
00:56:48,402 --> 00:56:50,502
but it should be moved to an archive.

998
00:56:51,043 --> 00:56:52,703
It is a pain when you search

999
00:56:53,164 --> 00:56:55,204
and half the results are from cut features.

1000
00:56:56,065 --> 00:56:59,226
Know when to collate certain types of information

1001
00:56:59,546 --> 00:57:00,487
into a single doc.

1002
00:57:01,247 --> 00:57:01,867
It's mind-numbing.

1003
00:57:02,389 --> 00:57:06,492
to have to search through 50 features pages to find the metrics you need.

1004
00:57:07,593 --> 00:57:13,098
And the most critical point, do you want good bugs? Bugs that are

1005
00:57:13,238 --> 00:57:18,962
accurate, relevant, and thorough? Testing teams cannot do this without good

1006
00:57:19,163 --> 00:57:23,426
documentation. Okay, we're almost done.

1007
00:57:25,948 --> 00:57:29,711
Flexible metrics can save you from determinism in game design.

1008
00:57:30,216 --> 00:57:33,520
freeing outcomes through an attentive give and take between teams.

1009
00:57:34,221 --> 00:57:38,026
Key partnerships must be empowering one another to pivot,

1010
00:57:38,407 --> 00:57:41,250
rather than siloing work and racing to the finish line.

1011
00:57:41,771 --> 00:57:45,436
Tools creation can focus on procedural solutions when possible

1012
00:57:45,736 --> 00:57:48,820
and develop ergonomic tools alongside the feature when not.

1013
00:57:49,561 --> 00:57:54,543
Documentation should be treated as a game development task, not something that's tacked on

1014
00:57:54,863 --> 00:58:01,006
to existing tasks. It needs as much production guidance as anything that will go into the game

1015
00:58:01,066 --> 00:58:09,550
itself. So that's the plan. Nine solutions to eight challenges. As I think you've noticed,

1016
00:58:09,710 --> 00:58:13,152
it's a lot of hard work and involves nearly everyone on the team.

1017
00:58:13,686 --> 00:58:16,429
And I couldn't even get into topics like recruitment,

1018
00:58:16,549 --> 00:58:18,971
the impact of marketing, user research,

1019
00:58:19,592 --> 00:58:22,234
all the ways that we depend on producers

1020
00:58:22,335 --> 00:58:23,295
and build management.

1021
00:58:23,376 --> 00:58:25,998
And I barely scratched the surface concerning QA.

1022
00:58:26,779 --> 00:58:30,442
But I think this is a good start and can lead to discussions

1023
00:58:30,483 --> 00:58:34,386
your team can have on how your entire studio can work together

1024
00:58:34,466 --> 00:58:36,048
to create great level design.

1025
00:58:36,974 --> 00:58:40,777
But GDC Talks are a studio and friendships wide effort.

1026
00:58:40,797 --> 00:58:45,161
So thank all of you for taking the time to help me with this,

1027
00:58:45,281 --> 00:58:48,404
especially while we're trying to get Deathloop out the door.

1028
00:58:48,424 --> 00:58:50,646
I couldn't have done it without you.

1029
00:58:50,666 --> 00:58:54,310
It's over! Thank you.

